In 1914 the Greek revolutionary authority of Chimarra issued a set of 4 values in a very small quantity. At that time postal service of that area was limited and only few copies are saved to nowadays.

This first issue of Northern Epirus is known to collectors as the _Skulls_ or the _Chimarra Issue._ It was issued in February, 1914. Although this was a local issue the stamps can be found with genuine cancellatons of 'Delvinon' and 'Agioi Saranta'. They were printed on rice paper by the use of rubber handstamps. The rubber handstamps were used in three distinct operations:

- image of the stamp
- impression of the value
- impression of the monogram of Spyromilios.

One can distinguish four kinds of printings:

- Genuine stamps.
- Printings by means of genuine handstamps on similar paper to above, known as the 'first Spetsiotis reprints'.
- Printings b means of genuine handstamps on different thicker paper.
- Total forgeries. 


