###First Stamps
The first stamps associated with Epirus were issued at Himar in February 1914. The set of four (1, 5, 10, and 25 lepta) are large stamps prominently featuring a double-headed eagle along with a skull and crossbones, and inscribed  (Greek Autonomous Epirus - Freedom or Death - Defend our Country") . Produced manually with a handstamp, they also have a control mark on the back consisting of a blue oval with the letters  inside, after Spyros Spyromilios, the commander at Chimarra. Some experts argue that these do not qualify as official stamp issues; even so, a set of four is worth about US$700.
